Bis Catilinam] Manutius has a long note in proof that Catiline was acquitted in three prosecutions: (1) for the seduction of Fabia, a vestal virgin, (2) for the murder of Gratidianus, (3) for malversation in his province. For the omission of the first in the present instance he accounts by the fact that Fabia was the sister of Terentia, and that Cicero had always maintained her innocence of the crime. lt would be absurd therefore to refer to the prosecution as evidence of Catilines guilt.
